00:46:53,281 --> 00:46:58,663
To speak on public buildings, the Brooks Estate, and Medford Public Library.

648
00:46:59,243 --> 00:46:59,543
Ms.

649
00:46:59,623 --> 00:47:00,723
Martin, welcome.

650
00:47:00,804 --> 00:47:02,744
Please state your name and address for the record.

651
00:47:02,844 --> 00:47:04,145
Jean Martin, 10 Cummings Street.

652
00:47:04,865 --> 00:47:06,886
Thank you very much for giving me this opportunity to speak.

653
00:47:09,183 --> 00:47:12,446
The Brooks Estates needs to be dealt with.

654
00:47:12,506 --> 00:47:14,989
It needs to be put to rest once and for all.

655
00:47:15,850 --> 00:47:19,093
They've tried to come up with the money for it, and they can't.

656
00:47:19,193 --> 00:47:23,537
They can't come up with private funding, and there are some issues up there that I need to talk about.

657
00:47:23,557 --> 00:47:28,802
But first, I just want to say, we have to remember that the Brooks Estates

658
00:47:30,390 --> 00:47:34,253
comes out of the history, a darker point in our history.

659
00:47:34,973 --> 00:47:35,814
They were blue bloods.

660
00:47:36,955 --> 00:47:40,858
They made their money off of the shipping industry, the insurance of the industry.

661
00:47:42,419 --> 00:47:45,401
They insured the ships that were involved in the triangular trade.

662
00:47:46,282 --> 00:47:54,588
So they literally made their money off of slavery and rum, and if there were fires or piracy, they insured against those things.

663
00:47:54,628 --> 00:47:56,630
So we just have to keep that in mind when we go forward.

664
00:47:58,971 --> 00:47:59,812
They insured the cargo.

665
00:48:00,451 --> 00:48:02,332
that included enslaved Africans.

666
00:48:02,932 --> 00:48:10,176
The Brooks family also owned slaves, so the beautiful carriage house was built with blood money.

667
00:48:11,817 --> 00:48:21,763
The well-meaning group of volunteers have not been able to find donors to support the $3.5 million it takes to renovate the place for occupancy.

668
00:48:23,680 --> 00:48:32,066
Speaking of occupancy, I hear that there are people living in that house which in no way could possibly pass today's codes.

669
00:48:32,547 --> 00:48:39,111
So Mr. Knight, I'm glad we have another person that can check out the buildings, because I want somebody up there checking out that building for occupancies.

670
00:48:40,933 --> 00:48:50,700
Also, there is going to be, or might be, I don't know if the baby happened or if it's going to happen, but I heard a rumor that this is a young couple and they could have a baby.

671
00:48:53,024 --> 00:48:53,724
That's a problem.

672
00:48:54,665 --> 00:48:58,067
That house must have lead paint, electrical and plumbing deficiencies.

673
00:48:58,807 --> 00:49:11,735
I'm a landlord and I hold a certificate of occupancy, an inspection from my insurance company, carbon monoxide alarms, a stove, income taxes with all receipts for repairs, home insurance, and a 21-page lease.

674
00:49:12,936 --> 00:49:15,237
And I own a two-family house, okay?

675
00:49:15,537 --> 00:49:16,878
That's just for the renters downstairs.

676
00:49:18,238 --> 00:49:26,924
We, the entire city of Medford, are on the hook for any accident or incident that may happen on that property, not just the Brooks volunteers.

677
00:49:28,446 --> 00:49:36,852
It is time to move the occupants out, even if it costs the city to move them out, to do it and tear down the buildings once and for all.

678
00:49:38,033 --> 00:49:47,720
I know that it's hard for those people that put so much time and energy and effort into it, but then they're not the only ones that have other ideas for the city

679
00:49:49,568 --> 00:49:50,849
I have ideas for the city too.

680
00:49:52,010 --> 00:49:57,894
I would love to have that dance hall taken down so that when you come off the highway you see this beautiful structure called the people's house.

681
00:49:59,015 --> 00:50:08,402
I would love to take the library, invest three and a half million dollars, put another level on there and call it an art center or something so that we can maintain

682
00:50:09,635 --> 00:50:16,521
still maintain a library, make it more useful for modern day people because we have the internet and people don't use the library.

683
00:50:16,782 --> 00:50:21,987
But if we made it a library slash art center, maybe we could continue that public building.

684
00:50:23,728 --> 00:50:30,975
But I can't do that in good conscience and look at the police department, the police personnel, the DPW, the streets, the plumbing

685
00:50:32,080 --> 00:50:34,061
The sewer pipes that aren't getting any younger.

686
00:50:34,081 --> 00:50:36,661
The buildings in this area that aren't getting any younger.

687
00:50:37,241 --> 00:50:38,082
I can't do that.

688
00:50:38,122 --> 00:50:39,402
I can't look them in the eye.

689
00:50:39,422 --> 00:50:40,682
I can't look the buildings in the eye.

690
00:50:40,742 --> 00:50:42,683
God knows this one could use three and a half million.

691
00:50:44,623 --> 00:50:45,183
It just goes on.

692
00:50:49,984 --> 00:50:52,205
I also want a center for kids in Haines Square.

693
00:50:52,625 --> 00:50:54,125
That's another one of my pluses.

694
00:50:54,165 --> 00:50:55,986
That's another one of my dream sheets.

695
00:50:57,646 --> 00:51:00,867
What I'm saying is that it's a luxury to have the Brooks Estates.

696
00:51:01,415 --> 00:51:03,296
And it's one that we can't afford, and we've got to put it to rest.

697
00:51:03,376 --> 00:51:03,956
It's got to end.

698
00:51:04,577 --> 00:51:10,300
Because we have to get on with the really serious issues that this city is facing in economics and everything else.

699
00:51:11,380 --> 00:51:18,804
And I've spoken to some old timers, and they don't want it to be even remained as a green space.

700
00:51:19,405 --> 00:51:21,806
They look at that Brooks Estates, and they go, oh, plots.

701
00:51:22,967 --> 00:51:24,267
They have plots in their head.

702
00:51:24,508 --> 00:51:27,849
They're dying, their friends are dying, and they want to be buried here in Medford.

703
00:51:28,290 --> 00:51:28,870
And they see it.

704
00:51:30,175 --> 00:51:31,736
as future burial ground.

705
00:51:32,897 --> 00:51:38,042
I'm not suggesting that we do that, but I'm saying that there are a lot of people who would just like to turn that into that.

706
00:51:38,262 --> 00:51:45,087
If you want to keep it as a green space, I'm okay with that, but we have to put to rest the house, the structure, and everything else.

707
00:51:45,668 --> 00:51:52,734
That said, the $3.5 million needs to go towards a new police station and to fund 15 more police officers.

708
00:51:53,454 --> 00:51:55,536
We need more DPW workers for the streets.

709
00:51:56,023 --> 00:52:03,629
which need to be regularly swept, striped, crosswalks, squares need some life, like flower buckets and lighting.

710
00:52:04,570 --> 00:52:05,871
There are many needs in this city.

711
00:52:05,911 --> 00:52:12,517
The Brooks Estates has got to put this to rest, and the city can come together on what we really need to do.

712
00:52:13,117 --> 00:52:15,219
Needs and wants are two different things.

713
00:52:16,140 --> 00:52:19,683
Again, I want to thank those people that have put their attention into it.

714
00:52:20,603 --> 00:52:23,705
But they've got to realize that their dream isn't going to end.

715
00:52:23,765 --> 00:52:31,251
And they should get about six months to decompress and cry and grieve, because it just has to come to an end.

716
00:52:31,892 --> 00:52:32,232
Thank you.

717
00:52:32,252 --> 00:52:34,634
Thank you very much, Ms.

718
00:52:34,654 --> 00:52:34,734
Todd.

719
